message: Important citations were removed and presentation suffered. Also footfalls' citation should come from reputable trading magazines with independent tracking system like Box Office India whose figures are generally accepted in the trade and media and not small sites like Indicine or Addatoday with no any research body and pure estimations.
@kailash29792 removed the second part of the edit as it was present in 3rd para but its worldwide stand wasn't
Nett collection was mentioned not gross.
For gross records check accolades section. Additionally 4 of his films were highest grossers in the country at some of point of time.

@kailash29792 please look for the wiki link attached (1960 in film) regarding gross figure and also check the Wikipedia page for the list of movies with highest box-office admissions. There is no film even close to the admissions of Mughal-e-Azam in 1960.

message: Gunga Jumna (1961) and Naya Daur (1957) will also gross over 1000 crore when adjusted to ticket price inflation at 200 times as in the case of Mughal-e-Azam (1960) and Mother India (1957). They were not missed before. Also $61 million of Jugnu in 1947 is more than than $60.9 million of Nagin (1954) when adjusted for inflation and not equal.

message: A single article source which sounds more like an opinion piece can't justify such a grand claim. "Greatest" artist is not simply the best selling artist. It has more to do with the kind of work they did, their impact, etc.
His credentials as a director is first and foremost. As his reputation is largely based on that only.
No need for the reference of some blog type articles.
Mother was released in October 1957. It was not released around Pyaasa which was released in Feb 1957.
Don't revert anything without verifying. Mainly fixed some typo.

Don't revert anything without verifying. Added more substantial information mostly in Artistry and legacy section as it consisted of very sparse information, not really revealing anything about his legacy for a new reader. Other sections like that of his personal life are also very bleak with half information and several absent information about his relationships among others. Changes in the language, if any, are welcome.
Shifted a very small part of introduction to accolades section as it was not worthy of mention there.
Refined citations. Improved personal life section.
Refined accolades section. Merged certain citations.
Added another citation related to the details of the interview
A very important addition in context to "The Superstar title of Rajesh Khanna" which needs to be right on the introduction page.
Combined many citations and added few more. Also removed few unnecessary ones.
Commercial record added in introduction part
Changed image. Linked a more clearer image than previous one.

Opinions of few artists in a biography (published as early as 1972) cannot become representative or central to the person's introduction or legacy. Only a wide consensus and apt explanation can justify the claim to such a grand statement because there are enough personal opinions for other artists as well.
The budget given earlier was of Shakti Samanta Devadas (2002). This one is relatively credible.

Reverted the very last edit. The mention was about consecutive Filmfare best actor award wins not just any filmfare award. Abhishek Bachchan hasn't won 3 Filmfare award for best actor. The reference to the superlatives of Filmfare best actor award is linked already.
Linked "Superlatives" section of "Filmfare award for Best Actor" page highlighting consecutive no of wins record.

Mention of his other occasionally dubbed names, Tragedy King and First Khan is already in the Artistry and Legacy section. Both these terms are magazine/media originated, and the latter retrospective one is surely a recently one, hence I highlighted here the title by which he has been generally addressed by the masses, media and critics alike since the beginning.

page: List of highest-grossing films in India
message: Coolie (1983) footfalls are ludicrous and incorrect. While grossing ₹16 crore, Vidhaata (1982) has 38 million footfalls. And Coolie while grossing ₹18 crore, collects 70 million footfalls at the same ATP. That is impossible. An opinion piece from back in the day was cited as source when there were no measures to track box office admissions. Same can be said for Shaan(1980), a box office dud, for whose collection, it's directors opinion is cited from 1984, which contradicts current trade analysis
Serious portrayals equate to drama in theatrical terms.
He was not a film producer by profession, he only produced one film of his own, namely Gunga Jumna (1961).
Bachchan won the Filmfare Award for Best Supporting Actor three consecutive times not the Best Actor award.

message: Gross of Rs 100 million in 1955 is impossible as then it would be the highest grossing Indian film up till then. It would gross even more than Mother India which was to become the highest grossing Indian film of all time in 1957. This never happened and is practically impossible for a regional art film with no wide screening except Calcutta to gross that much in total either in India or overseas. And so  I've provided detail of its gross till 1980 which is much less than the previous source data
